Characterization of the Microbiome of a State-of-the-Art Water Reuse System to Enhance Treatment Performance

This is an R Markdown Notebook. When you execute code within the notebook, the results appear beneath the code. Try executing this chunk by clicking the Run button within the chunk or by placing your cursor inside it and pressing Cmd+Shift+Enter.

Before figure generation and analyses in R, I process my data in QIIME and deblur- the below is exicsed from a BASH script used to run the initial processing outside of R.

Note that for all QIIME/UPARSE related scripts I’m operating in the BASH environment. Depending on your computer you may have problems running more memory intensive steps, e.g. taxonomy assignment and sequence alignment. Prior to R for visualization and analysis, I used an M4.4xlarge instance on Amazon EC2.

You will need the initial mapping files for QC, as well as the analysis mapping (Both included in supplementary data on the github repo) file to recreate this analysis.

Software used: - QIIME 1.9.1 - USEARCH v. 10.0.240 - PEAR - All dependencies for the above software

I run QIIME and Deblur within separate virtual environments, so you’ll see me activate and deactivate them within this script. The first several blocks of code were carried out using an t2.medium instance type. For storage, I recommend 80-100 GB.

bashbash source activate qiime1

By the estimated insert sizes for 16S and 18S, we’re going to have to process our Bacterial/Archaeal and Eukaryotic sequences separately- 18S reads will not join (≈600-700 bp, so no overlap). First, we’ll join reads, and then use the unpaired reads into a separate USEARCH pipeline.

bashbash pear -f seq/BS-S1_S1_L001_R1_001.fastq -r seq/July2017/BS-S1_S1_L001_R2_001.fastq -o seq/seqs -p 0.001 -v 50 -m 450 -n 250 -y 500m -j 16

pear -f seq/Parada_Run1_Early2017_R1.fastq -r seq/Parada_Run1_Early2017_R2.fastq -o seq/seqs -p 0.001 -v 50 -m 450 -n 250 -y 500m -j 16

After assembly, we’re going to bifurcate into two workflows- the joined (Bacterial/Archaeal) and unjoined (Mostly Eukaryotic) sequences. Unjoined will use the unpaired, raw sequence data. I’ll need to process both the R1 and R2 files to capture all of the sequence reads with a valid barcode and forward primer sequence because of my design.

bashbash extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -a -m map.txt -f seq/July/seqs.assembled.fastq -o seq/July/PreppedJoined/ extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -f seq/July/BS-S1_S1_L001_R1_001.fastq -o seq/July/PreppedF/ extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -f seq/July/BS-S1_S1_L001_R2_001.fastq -o seq/July/PreppedR/

extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -a -m OctoberMap.txt -f seq/October/seqs.assembled.fastq -o seq/October/PreppedJoined/ extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -f seq/Parada_Run1_Early2017_R1.fastq -o seq/October/PreppedF/ extract_barcodes.py -l 12 -f seq/Parada_Run1_Early2017_R2.fastq -o seq/October/PreppedR/

Onto demultiplexing. No quality filtering was performed at this point, since the USEARCH pipeline will take the FASTQ file and filter later on.

bashbash split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/July/PreppedJoined/reads.fastq -b seq/July/PreppedJoined/barcodes.fastq -m JulyMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/July/SlOutJoin/

split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/July/PreppedF/reads.fastq -b seq/July/PreppedF/barcodes.fastq -m JulyMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/July/SlOut_F/

split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/July/PreppedR/reads.fastq -b seq/July/PreppedR/barcodes.fastq -m JulyMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/July/SlOut_R/

mkdir seq/July/SlOutUn/ cat seq/July/SlOut_F/seqs.fna seq/July/SlOut_R/seqs.fna > seq/July/SlOutUn/seqs.fna cat seq/July/SlOut_F/seqs.fastq seq/July/SlOut_R/seqs.fastq > seq/July/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq

split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/October/PreppedJoined/reads.fastq -b seq/October/PreppedJoined/barcodes.fastq -m OctoberMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/October/SlOutJoin/

split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/October/PreppedF/reads.fastq -b seq/October/PreppedF/barcodes.fastq -m OctoberMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/October/SlOut_F/

split_libraries_fastq.py –barcode_type 12 -i seq/October/PreppedR/reads.fastq -b seq/October/PreppedR/barcodes.fastq -m OctoberMap.txt –phred_quality_threshold 0 –store_demultiplexed_fastq -o seq/October/SlOut_R/

mkdir seq/October/SlOutUn/ cat seq/October/SlOut_F/seqs.fna seq/October/SlOut_R/seqs.fna > seq/October/SlOutUn/seqs.fna cat seq/October/SlOut_F/seqs.fastq seq/October/SlOut_R/seqs.fastq > seq/October/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq

mkdir seq/SlOutJoin/ cat seq/July/SlOutJoin/seqs.fna seq/October/SlOutJoin/seqs.fna > seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.fna cat seq/July/SlOutJoin/seqs.fastq seq/October/SlOutJoin/seqs.fastq > seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.fastq

mkdir seq/SlOutUn/ cat seq/July/SlOutUn/seqs.fna seq/October/SlOutUn/seqs.fna > seq/SlOutUn/seqs.fna cat seq/July/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq seq/October/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq > seq/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq

Now, onto USEARCH

bashbash mkdir UPARSE mkdir UPARSE/Join/ usearch -fastx_truncate seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.fastq -trunclen 400 -fastqout seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.trunc.fastq usearch -fastx_truncate seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.fna -trunclen 400 -fastaout seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.trunc.fna usearch -fastq_filter seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.trunc.fastq -fastaout UPARSE/Join/seqs.filtered.fasta -fastq_maxee 1 usearch -fastx_uniques UPARSE/Join/seqs.filtered.fasta -fastaout UPARSE/Join/uniques.fa -sizeout -relabel Uniq usearch -unoise3 UPARSE/Join/uniques.fa -zotus UPARSE/Join/zotus.fa usearch -usearch_global seq/SlOutJoin/seqs.fna -db UPARSE/Join/zotus.fa -strand plus -id 0.99 -uc UPARSE/Join/zotu.map.uc python /usr/bin/uc2otutab.py UPARSE/Join/zotu.map.uc > UPARSE/Join/zotu-table.txt biom convert –table-type=table -i UPARSE/Join/zotu-table.txt -o UPARSE/Join/zotu.biom –to-json assign_taxonomy.py -m mothur -t /media/Storage/DB/silva.nr_v128.tax -r /media/Storage/DB/silva.nr_v128.align -o UPARSE/Join/mothur_taxonomy/ -i UPARSE/Join/zotus.fa biom add-metadata –sc-separated taxonomy –observation-header OTUID,taxonomy –observation-metadata-fp UPARSE/Join/mothur_taxonomy/zotus_tax_assignments.txt -i UPARSE/Join/zotu.biom -o UPARSE/Join/zotu_w_tax.biom biom add-metadata -i UPARSE/Join/zotu_w_tax.biom -o UPARSE/Join/zotu_w_md.biom –sample-metadata-fp map.txt

mkdir UPARSE/Un/ usearch -fastq_filter seq/SlOutUn/seqs.fastq -fastaout UPARSE/Un/seqs.filtered.fasta -fastq_maxee 1 usearch -fastx_uniques UPARSE/Un/seqs.filtered.fasta -fastaout UPARSE/Un/uniques.fa -sizeout -relabel Uniq usearch -unoise3 UPARSE/Un/uniques.fa -zotus UPARSE/Un/zotus.fa usearch -usearch_global seq/SlOutUn/seqs.fna -db UPARSE/Un/zotus.fa -strand plus -id 0.99 -uc UPARSE/Un/zotu.map.uc python /usr/bin/uc2otutab.py UPARSE/Un/zotu.map.uc > UPARSE/Un/zotu-table.txt biom convert –table-type=table -i UPARSE/Un/zotu-table.txt -o UPARSE/Un/zotu.biom –to-json assign_taxonomy.py -m mothur -t /media/Storage/DB/silva.nr_v128.tax -r /media/Storage/DB/silva.nr_v128.align -o UPARSE/Un/mothur_taxonomy/ -i UPARSE/Un/zotus.fa biom add-metadata –sc-separated taxonomy –observation-header OTUID,taxonomy –observation-metadata-fp UPARSE/Un/mothur_taxonomy/zotus_tax_assignments.txt -i UPARSE/Un/zotu.biom -o UPARSE/Un/zotu_w_tax.biom biom add-metadata -i UPARSE/Un/zotu_w_tax.biom -o UPARSE/Un/zotu_w_md.biom –sample-metadata-fp map.txt

The next few steps are for filtering of contaminant sequences. I limited the control OTU table to samples with at least 1000 sequences to ensure that I could get a representative “contaminated” core microbiome. All extraction blanks and filtration blanks were identified within the “Sample” metadata category as “Control” within my mapping file.

Operational taxonomic units found to be in 75 percent of my controls will be removed. Also, because I have triplicate samples, I’ll assume any OTU not found in at least 3 samples is erroneous.

bashbash filter_samples_from_otu_table.py -m map.txt -s ‘Control:Y’ -n 1000 -o UPARSE/Join/Control.biom -i UPARSE/Join/zotu_w_md.biom compute_core_microbiome.py –min_fraction_for_core 0.25 –max_fraction_for_core 0.75 -i UPARSE/Join/Control.biom -o UPARSE/Join/ControlCore/

filter_otus_from_otu_table.py -e UPARSE/Join/ControlCore/core_otus_75.txt -s 3 -n 1 -i UPARSE/Join/zotu_w_md.biom -o UPARSE/Join/PostControlFilter.biom filter_taxa_from_otu_table.py -n Eukaryota -i UPARSE/Join/PostControlFilter.biom -o UPARSE/Join/AnalysisBacArc.biom filter_samples_from_otu_table.py -n 100 -i UPARSE/Join/AnalysisBacArc.biom -o UPARSE/Join/AnalysisBacArc.clean.biom

filter_samples_from_otu_table.py -m map.txt -s ‘Control:Y’ -n 1000 -o UPARSE/Un/Control.biom -i UPARSE/Un/zotu_w_md.biom compute_core_microbiome.py –min_fraction_for_core 0.25 –max_fraction_for_core 0.75 -i UPARSE/Un/Control.biom -o UPARSE/Un/ControlCore/

filter_otus_from_otu_table.py -e UPARSE/Un/ControlCore/core_otus_75.txt -s 3 -n 1 -i UPARSE/Un/zotu_w_md.biom -o UPARSE/Un/PostControlFilter.biom filter_taxa_from_otu_table.py -p Eukaryota -i UPARSE/Un/PostControlFilter.biom -o UPARSE/Un/Analysis_Euk.biom filter_samples_from_otu_table.py -n 100 -i UPARSE/Un/Analysis_Euk.biom -o UPARSE/Un/Analysis_Euk.clean.biom

Also, one BIOM file for a combined analysis, just to see the Eukarya/Bacteria ratio

filter_samples_from_otu_table.py -n 100 -i UPARSE/Un/PostControlFilter.biom -o UPARSE/Un/Analysis_combined.biom

Last step before moving into R. I’m going to extract sOTUs from the initial repset FASTA files to only include those that passed contamination screening. After this, I’ll align to the SILVA database, and then generate phylogenetic trees, useful for the Unifrac distance matrix.

bashbash filter_fasta.py -b UPARSE/Join/AnalysisBacArc.clean.biom -f UPARSE/Join/zotus.fa -o UPARSE/Join/BacArc.seqs.fna filter_fasta.py -b UPARSE/Un/Analysis_Euk.clean.biom -f UPARSE/Un/zotus.fa -o UPARSE/Un/Euk.seqs.fna

Combined

filter_fasta.py -b UPARSE/Un/Analysis_combined.biom -f UPARSE/Un/zotus.fa -o UPARSE/Un/All.seqs.fna

Back to the M4.4xlarge instance type for sequence alignment.

bashbash align_seqs.py -i UPARSE/Join/BacArc.seqs.fna -t /media/Storage/DB/SILVA_128_QIIME_release/rep_set_aligned/97/97_otus_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Join/Aligned/ filter_alignment.py -i UPARSE/Join/Aligned/BacArc.seqs_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Join/Aligned/ -e 0.001 make_phylogeny.py -i UPARSE/Join/Aligned/BacArc.seqs_aligned_pfiltered.fasta -o UPARSE/Join/BacArc.tre

align_seqs.py -i UPARSE/Un/Euk.seqs.fna -t /media/Storage/DB/SILVA_128_QIIME_release/rep_set_aligned/97/97_otus_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/Aligned/ filter_alignment.py -i UPARSE/Un/Aligned/Euk.seqs_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/Aligned/ -e 0.001 make_phylogeny.py -i UPARSE/Un/Aligned/Euk.seqs_aligned_pfiltered.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/Euk.tre

Combined

align_seqs.py -i UPARSE/Un/All.seqs.fna -t /media/Storage/DB/SILVA_128_QIIME_release/rep_set_aligned/97/97_otus_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/AllAligned/ filter_alignment.py -i UPARSE/Un/AllAligned/All.seqs_aligned.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/AllAligned/ -e 0.001 make_phylogeny.py -i UPARSE/Un/AllAligned/All.seqs_aligned_pfiltered.fasta -o UPARSE/Un/All.tre

Onto R. This can be run on (almost) any desktop/laptop without issue. In my case, I downloaded the above output files (.biom, .tre. and .fa) from my workstation onto my laptop to run the below.

Import BIOM files and convert to a phyloseq object. Also, I’ll need to rename the columns to match what Phyloseq/Ampvis expect and make my life a little simpler. This will be a large section as I import each file.

Overall.BA <- import_biom("AnalysisBacArc.clean.biom", "BacArc.tre", "BacArc.seqs.fna", parseFunction=parse_taxonomy_default)
Overall.E <- import_biom("Analysis_Euk.clean.biom", "Euk.tre", "Euk.seqs.fna", parseFunction=parse_taxonomy_default)

colnames(tax_table(Overall.E)) = c("Kingdom", "Phylum", "Class", "Order", "Family", "Genus", "Species")
